===Adjective===
{{en-adj|er|est}}

# {{not comparable}} No longer [[living]].
#: ''All of my grandparents are '''dead'''.''
# Figuratively, not [[alive]]; [[lack]]ing [[life]]
#* '''1600''', [[w:William Shakespeare]], ''[[w:As You Like It|As You Like It]]'', Act III, Scene 3
#*: "When a man's verses cannot be understood, nor a man's good wit seconded with the forward child, understanding, it strikes a man '''more dead''' than a great reckoning in a little room."
# {{not comparable}} {{italbrac|Of another person}} So [[hate]]d by that they are absolutely [[ignore]]d.
#: ''He is '''dead''' to me.''
# {{not comparable}} Fully and completely [[motionless]].
#: ''Come to a '''dead''' stop.''
# Without [[emotion]].
#: ''She stood with '''dead''' face and limp arms, unresponsive to my plea.''
# {{not comparable}} {{italbrac|Of a machine, device, or electrical circuit}} Completely [[inactive]]; without [[power]].
#: ''Ok, the circuit’s '''dead'''. Go ahead and cut the wire.''
#: ''Now that the motor’s '''dead''' you can reach in and extract the spark plugs.''
# {{not comparable}} [[broken|Broken]] or [[inoperable]].
#: ''That monitor is '''dead'''; don’t bother hooking it up.''
# {{not comparable|obsolete}} or no longer used or required.
#: ''There are several '''dead''' laws still on the books regulating where horses may be hitched.''
#: ''Is this beer glass '''dead''' ?''
# {{not comparable}} {{sports}} Not in [[play]].
#: ''Once the ball crosses the foul line, it’s '''dead'''.''
